[ProMED-mail thanks Dr Fonseca and colleagues for their submission above of the 2nd case human infection due to _Anaplasma phagocytophilum_ reported in Alberta, Canada.

Anaplasmosis due to _A. marginale_, is a nationally notifiable disease in Canada (http://www.inspection.gc.ca/animals/terrestrial-animals/diseases/immediately-notifiable/anaplasmosis/eng/1319738331963/1319810963903). _A. marginale_ is an obligate intra-erythrocytic parasite that affects domestic and wild ruminants, including cattle, sheep, goats and deer (http://www.inspection.gc.ca/animals/terrestrial-animals/diseases/immediately-notifiable/anaplasmosis/fact-sheet/eng/1329525231981/1329525339802). In Canada it is primarily a disease of cattle and is spread by ticks, as well a biting flies or through contaminated medical instruments. _A. marginale_ does not infect humans.

However, anaplasmosis due to _A. phagocytophilum_ is a zoonotic disease, which is called human granulocytic anaplasmosis (HGA) in humans. _A. phagocytophilum_ is an obligate intra-granulocytic parasite that is transmitted by _Ixodes scapularis_ and _I. pacificus_ in North America, and its distribution corresponds to that of Lyme disease, but at a much lower incidence.

At present HGA is reportable in Manitoba, but apparently not in any other jurisdiction in Canada, nor to the Public Health Agency of Canada (https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/publichealth/cdc/protocol/anaplasmosis.pdf).
Areas with evidence of _A. phagocytophilum_-infected blacklegged tick populations include Nova Scotia, New Brunswick, southern Quebec, eastern, southwestern & northwestern Ontario, and southern Manitoba, with the highest prevalence rates seen in Manitoba, New Brunswick, and Quebec (https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/publichealth/cdc/protocol/anaplasmosis.pdf).

Since HGA became provincially reportable on 1 Jan 2015 in Manitoba, there have been 21 cases of HGA in the province (https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/publichealth/cdc/tickborne/docs/tbd_report2016.pdf). One case of HGA has previously been reported in Alberta (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2770309/). No human cases have been reported so far in Nova Scotia or in New Brunswick (https://novascotia.ca/dhw/cdpc/documents/2017_Tick_Borne_Disease_Response_Plan.pdf and http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dog-diseases-enter-new-brunswick-1.4209193, respectively).

However, infection with _A. phagocytophilum_ has been reported in other animals (https://books.google.com/books?id=9GsWDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18&dq=anaplasmosis+in+canada+gideon&source): a dog in British Columbia (http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S187603410800004X), 3 dogs (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2711468/) and 1 horse (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3398529/) in Saskatchewan, a horse in Ontario https://www.wormsandgermsblog.com/2015/11/articles/animals/horses/equine-anaplasmosis-ontario/), and a horse in Nova Scotia (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3078012/).

Maps of Canada: http://mapsof.net/uploads/static-maps/canada_provinces_and_territories_map.png (provinces) and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5522625,263

A picture of the intra-cytoplasmic inclusions called morulae due to _A. phagocytophilum_ can be found at
http://www.medscape.com/content/2004/00/49/04/490468/art-iim490468.fig1.jpg.

A photograph of _Ixodes scapularis_ (blacklegged tick) can be seen at
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ixodes_scapularis. - Mod.ML]
